{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17598281","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17598281"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:35:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:35:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15459"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15459","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15459"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.02,0.02,0.84,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8150"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66621"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8150","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8150"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15459"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52074"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1144"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"7200"},{"type":"tags","id":"7215"},{"type":"tags","id":"8201"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19748"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19755"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22231"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66621","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66621"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman undergoes a total thyroidectomy for Graves disease. During her recovery she has a persistent hoarseness. On laryngoscopy, her right vocal cord is immobile in a paramedian position.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Damage to which one of the following nerves is most likely to explain these findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Glossopharyngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Phrenic nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Superior laryngeal nerve"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eglossopharyngeal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (cranial nerve IX) gives inervation that is sensory to the posterior third of the tongue and pharynx, and parasympathetic supply to the parotid gland. The \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior laryngeal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E provides sensory innervation to the larynx above the vocal cords and motor supply to the cricothyroid muscle only.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Erecurrent laryngeal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is a branch of the vagus nerve that provides motor innervation to all intrinsic laryngeal muscles except the cricothyroid. Damage causes vocal cord paralysis and hoarseness. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ephrenic nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the diaphragm. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypoglossal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (cranial nerve XII) provides motor innervation to the tongue muscles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe recurrent laryngeal nerve is particularly vulnerable to injury during thyroid surgery due to its anatomical course around the subclavian artery on the right and the aortic arch on the left.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The recurrent laryngeal nerve innervates all intrinsic laryngeal muscles except the cricothyroid muscle","Damage to the recurrent laryngeal nerve causes vocal cord paralysis and hoarseness","The recurrent laryngeal nerve is a branch of the vagus nerve (cranial nerve X)"],"references":["Myssiorek D. Recurrent laryngeal nerve paralysis: anatomy and etiology. Otolaryngol Clin North Am. 2004 Feb;37(1):25-44, v. doi: 10.1016/S0030-6665(03)00172-5. PMID: 15062685.","Culp JM, Patel G. Recurrent Laryngeal Nerve Injury. [Updated 2023 May 22]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560832/","Reiter R, Hoffmann TK, Pickhard A, Brosch S. Hoarseness-causes and treatments. Dtsch Arztebl Int. 2015 May 8;112(19):329-37. doi: 10.3238/arztebl.2015.0329. PMID: 26043420; PMCID: PMC4458789.","House SA, Fisher EL. Hoarseness in Adults. Am Fam Physician. 2017 Dec 1;96(11):720-728. PMID: 29431404."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52074"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15459"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52074"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T16:41:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T16:44:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8150"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66621"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedA